pullRequest.body:
Add the widget to display string diagram of monoidal category morphism.

---
<!-- The text above the `---` will become the commit message when your
PR is merged. Please leave a blank newline before the `---`, otherwise
GitHub will format the text above it as a title.

To indicate co-authors, include lines at the bottom of the commit message
(that is, before the `---`) using the following format:

Co-authored-by: Author Name <author@email.com>

Any other comments you want to keep out of the PR commit should go
below the `---`, and placed outside this HTML comment, or else they
will be invisible to reviewers.

If this PR depends on other PRs, please list them below this comment,
using the following format:
- [ ] depends on: #abc [optional extra text]
- [ ] depends on: #xyz [optional extra text]
-->

### Issues

- ~~The widget fails to make a diagram for `f ▷ (X ⊗ Y)` without errors, although it succeeds for `(α_ X X Y).inv ≫ f ▷ X ▷ Y ≫ (α_ Y X Y).hom`. I expect the former expression to be rewritten to the latter by `eval`. There may be a bug somewhere, but I can't find it.~~ The problem was that the widget program can't find implicit arguments when using `mkAppM` (e.g. it can't find a `Category C` instance). I don't understand why this happens, but I removed all `mkAppM` and then the program works.

### Future plans (in another PR)

- [x] For `tensorHom`, the widget simply expand it by `tensorHom_def`. A better way is to allow `tensorHom` between non-composite morphisms, but this requires more works.  See #11080.
- [x] Supporting 2-morphisms in bicategories. See #12107.

> In this example:
> 
> ![image](https://private-user-images.githubusercontent.com/425260/305726370-4b4ed662-4661-4a54-9eae-63f5cffb9576.png?jwt=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJpc3MiOiJnaXRodWIuY29tIiwiYXVkIjoicmF3LmdpdGh1YnVzZXJjb250ZW50LmNvbSIsImtleSI6ImtleTUiLCJleHAiOjE3MDgyNzQ1NTcsIm5iZiI6MTcwODI3NDI1NywicGF0aCI6Ii80MjUyNjAvMzA1NzI2MzcwLTRiNGVkNjYyLTQ2NjEtNGE1NC05ZWFlLTYzZjVjZmZiOTU3Ni5wbmc_.I8KxEMV59LeYJlTDPQdnhgnYGh9zWGRAMwYR7Bmlp0g)
> 
> Should the middle `\` line be labelled `Y`?

Yes. Currently, the widget does not put labels to strings, but I think it is possible to add such a feature by editting the `monoidal.sty` file.

Now the widget supports `monoidalComp`. To support this, I redefined the normal form of 2-morphisms. The new normal form has the form `α₀ ≫ η₀ ≫ α₁ ≫ η₁ ≫ ... αₙ ≫ ηₙ ≫ αₙ₊₁`, where `αᵢ` are structural 2-morphisms and `ηᵢ` are non-structural 2-morphisms. See `NormalExpr`.

It seems a lot of this PR is about normalization in monoidal categories; is there a `moncat_normalize` tactic hiding here? Maybe such a tactic is out of scope for this Pr, but it would be good to put the content about normalization and the content about rendering in separate files, if such a split seems reasonable to you.
@eric-wieser Your suggestion makes sense to me. I will make a separate file that deals with normalization.

My inclination would be to rewrite this with Qq to make it more robust to metavariables / abbreviations / metadata.

I had a go at Qq-ifying this, but the best I could come up with was
```lean
/-- Evaluate the expression of a 2-morphism into a normalized form. -/
partial def eval {u v : Level} {α : Q(Type u)} {C : Q(Category.{v} $α)} {M : Q(MonoidalCategory $α)}
    {x y : Q($α)} (e : Q($x ⟶ $y)) : MetaM NormalExpr := do
  if let .defEq (h : $x =Q $y) ← isDefEqQ x y then
    if let ~q(𝟙 _) := e then
      return NormalExpr.id (toMor₁ x)
  if let ~q($f ≫ $g) := e then
    return evalComp (← eval f) (← eval g)
  if let ~q($xl ⊗ $xr) := x then
    if let ~q($yl ⊗ $yr) := y then
      if let .defEq (h : $xl =Q $yl) ← isDefEqQ xl yl then
        if let ~q(_ ◁ $η) := e then
          evalWhiskerLeftExpr (toMor₁ xl) (← eval η)
      if let .defEq (h : $xr =Q $yr) ← isDefEqQ xr yr then
        if let ~q($η ▷ _) := e then
          evalWhiskerRightExpr (← eval η) (toMor₁ xr)
  return NormalExpr.of e
  ```
  which doesn't actually work thanks to https://github.com/leanprover-community/quote4/issues/21. So I think Qq-ification is probably not on the cards after all.
Thank you very much for trying it! I knew very little about how to use Qq.
I think this is `List.enumFrom`?
Oh, I missed it, thanks!
`List.enum`

```lean
open Qq

variable {u v : Level} {C : Q(Type u)} {iC : Q(Category.{v} $C)} {iM : Q(MonoidalCategory $C)}
variable {X Y : Q($C)} (η : Q(𝟙_ _ ⟶ $X ⊗ $Y)) (ε : Q($Y ⊗ $X ⟶ 𝟙_ _))

#guard_msgs
#eval eval q(η ▷ X ≫ (α_ _ _ _).hom ≫ X ◁ ε)
```

Instead of having two presenters, how about having just one that shows both sides? That way it's easy to see the difference and what needs to be done to match the two sides up. @Vtec234 ~Now I need a slightly generalized version of `DiagramBuilderM` (see https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/10581/commits/035db686c6e5cb737315da22f636304e39e26ee0). Can you leave a comment mentioning why the RHS has no string diagram

This is because there are no non-structural morphisms in the RHS. I've tried to improve the message to make the situation clearer.

Probably a better way would be to display the trivial vertical strings instead of the text massage, but this would require some extra work, which I'd like to leave as a future work.

```suggestion
def mkContext? (e : Expr) : MetaM (Option Context) := do
```

I believe generally defs in `MetaM (Option ...)` should have a `?` at the end of their name.
I don't yet understand what the implications of these changes are and why they are necessary. Could you quickly explain please? Do you know why there used to be a `catch` which isn't needed anymore?

Previously I was using `ExprPresenter`, but then the normalization program had trouble generating proof terms for normalization. One reason was that the `MonoidalCategory C` instance in the assumptions was not available. In my understanding, tasks like generating proofs are beyond the scope of `ExprPresenter`.

In the current implementation of `StringDiagram.rpc` function, it explicitly deals with local instances using the `Meta.withLCtx` function.

> One reason was that the `MonoidalCategory C` instance in the assumptions was not available. In my understanding, tasks like generating proofs are beyond the scope of `ExprPresenter`.

Ah, no, that was an oversight in ProofWidgets. I pushed a fix for it now, and confirmed that your current code also works with `@[expr_presenter]` using updated ProofWidgets.

The real difference between `ExprPresenter`s and the panel widget approach is that the latter is more flexible but needs more boilerplate. With an `ExprPresenter`, your function can only process a single expression when computing the display, as opposed to integrating data from multiple local hypotheses (for instance multiple assumed equalities) in a single display. For this price, you do not have to add extra handling for multiple goals or for visualizing hypotheses.

Since visualizing a single expression is what you are doing now, maybe the limitation is okay? Do you anticipate a need for the flexibility of panel widgets later?

More generally, the `ExprPresenter` API doesn't get used much and I'm not sure if it's even needed. It would be nice to see a real use so that it can be either improved or retired (if we decide it's not useful).

Optional: Looking at the examples I had the idea that you could modify `fromExpr` with an optional argument so that in the case of equality, you get the text `no string diagram for RHS`/`.. for LHS`.

I was for a split-second confused why it displays one diagram plus "No string diagram" in one of the examples.

I would appreciate if you expand the doc a little bit with what a string diagram is and what you exactly implemented.

Can be a very brief/rudimentary, maybe including an almost trivial example, or a reference. Just so that the unfamiliar reader has some starting point.

Optional: Another optional suggestion, would it be simple to implement and useful (or looking neat) to have a `=` between the two diagrams in the widget? something like `

=

` with according style.

It is possible to have a `=` between the diagrams, but it may not be an immediate task to do so in a good format. For example, we may want to use the same font size as the string diagram, but I'm not sure how to do this. To be honest, I don't know much about HTML or JavaScript.
I think adding the texts like "LHS" and "RHS" instead (similar to your suggestion in another comment) would make it clearer that it is showing both sides of the equality.

```suggestion
      g.ctx.val.runMetaM {} do
        g.mvarId.withContext do
```
Iirc these are equivalent.

This is a little confusing to me (but I am not an n-categorist)! Are objects not 0-morphisms, and morphisms 1-morphisms? Then an example of 2-morphisms would be the natural transformations in Cat. (EDIT: Ok, I see the nLab says "2-categories are also a horizontal categorification of monoidal categories: they are like monoidal categories with many objects.". So when viewing C as a 1-category, the objects in C are 0-morphisms, but when viewing C as a 2-category with one object, the objects in C are 1-morphisms? That's not confusing at all :P)

Thank you for the comment. My explanation here wasn't very helpful. I added an explanation about the relationship between monoidal categories and bicategories and why I used bicategory terminology in this file.
Since `GoalTypePanel` can also draw this now using the presenter, should we get rid of this and the `StringDiagram` component?

Both are fine. Since `GoalTypePanel` is for more general purposes, in specialised situations I may want to use the current `StringDiagram` (Also, it was useful for debugging.). But I'm not sure it's worth keeping this rpc method.

I see! Yes, there is no good way to debug `ExprPresenter`s right now. I am assuming that you need to keep the rpc method if you want to keep `StringDiagram`, as the rpc method is its main implementation!
Isn't this `fun l => l.zip (l.drop 1)`
I wonder if there is any value to using something unboxed like `UInt` in place of `Nat`.
Similarly, here and below, there is probably a performance benefit swapping out `List` for `Array` but I don't know what size the diagrams need to be before it is realized.
I would say no diagram you'd want to see in practice is large enough for this to make a meaningful difference. But I haven't benchmarked it, only tasseomancied.
I agree. I think the direct `Expr` manipulation might be the best place to look for a real world improvement. This is also something that can be thought about afterwards.
